sentences: Moacir Santos was born in Flores do Pajeú, Pernambuco in 1926.
By the 1950s, Santos was living in Rio de Janeiro and worked for Rádio Nacional as a composer.
In 1965, Santos released the album Coisas (translating to "things" in Portuguese) on the Forma record label.
After composing a number of scores for Brazilian films throughout the 1960s, Santos had the opportunity to move to the United States.
In 1967, Santos and his wife, Cleonice, moved to Pasadena, California, with the intent of breaking into the film industry.
Santos recorded three albums for Blue Note in the 1970s.
His 1972 release, Maestro, was nominated for a Grammy award.
In 2001, fellow Brazilians Zé Nogueira and Mario Adnet arranged sessions to re-record some of Santos' compositions.
These recordings would form the 2004 album Ouro Negro which featured performances from Milton Nascimento, Joao Donato and Gilberto Gil.
His final album, Choros & Alegria, was released in 2005.
In 2006, Santos died due to complications from an earlier stroke at an assisted living facility in Pasadena, California.

During the 1950s and 1960s, Santos privately taught a number of young Bossa Nova musicians such as Nara Leao, Baden Powell, Carlos Lyra and Roberto Menescal.

sentences: Moacir Santos (26 July 1926 – 6 August 2006) was a Brazilian composer, multi-instrumentalist and music educator.
His mother died when he was two years old, and as his father had already left the family, he was taken in by another family.
